{"title_page": "South Carolina Highway 700", "text_new": "{{Infobox road\n|state=SC\n|type=SC\n|route=700\n|alternate_name=Maybank Highway\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-lat=32.689|frame-long=-80.083|zoom=10|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/South Carolina Highway 700}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|length_mi=20.38\n|length_round=2\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"SCDOT GIS\"/>\n|established=\n|direction_a=West\n|terminus_a=[[Dead end (street)|Dead end]] in [[Rockville, South Carolina|Rockville]]\n|junction={{Jct|state=SC|SC|171}} in [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]]\n|direction_b=East\n|terminus_b={{Jct|state=SC|US|17}} in Charleston\n|counties=[[Charleston County, South Carolina|Charleston]]\n|previous_type=SC\n|previous_route=692\n|next_type=SC\n|next_route=702\n}}\n\n'''South Carolina Highway 700''' ('''SC 700''') is a [[state highway]] in the U.S. state of [[South Carolina]]. Known for most of its length as Maybank Highway, the state highway runs {{convert|20.38|mi|km}} from a [[Dead end (street)|dead end]] in [[Rockville, South Carolina|Rockville]] east to [[U.S. Route 17 in South Carolina|U.S. Highway 17]] (US 17) in [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]]. SC 700 connects Charleston with [[James Island (South Carolina)|James Island]], [[Johns Island, South Carolina|Johns Island]], and [[Wadmalaw Island]] in southwestern [[Charleston County, South Carolina|Charleston County]].\n\n==Route description==\nSC 700 begins at a dead end in the town of Rockville on Wadmalaw Island. The terminus is on the north side of Bohicket Creek, which separates Wadmalaw Island from [[Seabrook Island]], a short distance east of Bohicket Creek's mouth on the [[Edisto River|North Edisto River]]. The state highway heads northeast as Maybank Highway, a two-lane road that passes by the [[Charleston Tea Plantation]], the only working tea plantation in the United States, and near the [[Firefly Distillery]], which is on Bear Bluff Road on the portion of the island north of Leadenwah Creek. SR 700 crosses Church Creek onto Johns Island, enters an outlying section of the city of Charleston, and arrives at the main crossroads of the island near the site of the venerable [[Angel Oak]]. Main Road heads north from the junction through the northern part of the island before crossing the [[Stono River]] on the [[John F. Limehouse Memorial Bridge]] to meet US 17 between [[Rantowles, South Carolina|Rantowles]] and Charleston. Bohicket Road heads south toward Seabrook Island and Kiawah Island. SC 700 continues east and near the eastern end of the island intersects River Road, which leads south to [[Charleston Executive Airport]].<ref name=\"SCDOT County Maps\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps SC 700\"/>\n\nSC 700 expands to four lanes and crosses Pennys Creek and the Stono River on the high-level [[Paul Gelegotis Bridge]] and enters James Island. The highway passes through a golf course and along the south side of the historic [[Riverland Terrace]] neighborhood. SC 700 continues into a commercial area where the highway has a [[wye (rail)|wye]]-type junction with [[South Carolina Highway 171|SC 171]] (Folly Road) west of the [[McLeod Plantation]] and Charleston Country Club. Old Folly Road is used for the movements from eastbound SC 700 to southbound SC 171 and from northbound SC 171 to westbound SC 700. SC 700 and SC 171 head north concurrently on Folly Road, which has two lanes northbound and three lanes southbound. The highways enter the [[West Ashley]] section of Charleston by crossing Wappoo Creek, part of the [[Intracoastal Waterway]], on a [[Wappoo Creek Bridge|drawbridge]] named for [[Burnet R. Maybank]]. SC 700 and SC 171 diverge at a directional intersection that does not allow access from southbound SR 171 to eastbound SC 700. SC 171 heads north as Wesley Drive and is used to access southbound US 17 (Savannah Highway) and [[South Carolina Highway 61|SC 61]] (St. Andrews Boulevard). SC 700 heads northeast as five-lane Folly Road (three lanes westbound and two lanes eastbound) to its eastern terminus at a partial interchange with US 17 just west of the U.S. Highway's interchange with SC 61 and its bridges over the [[Ashley River (South Carolina)|Ashley River]]. The interchange allows access between SC 700 and US 17 in the direction of the peninsular section of Charleston.<ref name=\"SCDOT County Maps\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps SC 700\"/>\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{jcttop|length_ref=<ref name=\"SCDOT GIS\"/>|state=SC|county=Charleston}}\n{{SCint\n|location=Rockville\n|mile=0.00\n|road=[[Dead end (street)|Dead end]]\n|notes=Western terminus\n}}\n{{SCint\n|location=Charleston\n|lspan=3\n|mile=18.99\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=SC|SC|171|dir1=south|name1=Folly Road|city1=Folly Beach}}\n|notes=Western end of SC&nbsp;171 concurrency\n}}\n{{SCint\n|mile=19.96\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=SC|SC|171|dir1=north|name1=Wesley Drive|to2=y|US|17|dir2=south|SC|61|city1=North Charleston|location2=[[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]]}}\n|notes=Eastern end of SC&nbsp;171 concurrency\n}}\n{{SCint\n|mile=20.38\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=SC|US|17|dir1=north|name1=Savannah Highway|city1=Charleston|city2=Mount Pleasant}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus; southbound exit from and northbound entrance to US&nbsp;17\n}}\n{{Jctbtm|keys=concur,incomplete}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"SCDOT GIS\">{{cite map|publisher=[[South Carolina Department of Transportation]]|title=Highways - Zipped Shapefile of roads maintained by SCDOT - Statewide|url=http://dbw.scdot.org/GISMapping/pdfs/GIS/Statewide_Highways_2012.zip|format=ESRI shapefile|year=2012|accessdate=2012-05-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Google Maps SC 700\">{{google maps|url=https://maps.google.com/maps?saddr=S+Carolina+700+E&daddr=Folly+Rd&hl=en&sll=32.600952,-80.192868&sspn=0.00442,0.010568&geocode=FVxv8QEdGFU4-w%3BFTQv9AEd2Mg7-w&t=h&mra=ls&z=11|title=South Carolina Highway 700|accessdate=2012-05-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"SCDOT County Maps\">{{cite web|url=http://dbw.scdot.org/GISMapping/default.aspx|title=General County Highway Maps|publisher=South Carolina Department of Transportation|accessdate=2012-05-31}}\n*[http://dbw.scdot.org/GISMapping/pdfs/County/Charleston_County.pdf Charleston County] (PDF)\n</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML}}\n{{commonscat}}\n*[http://www.angelfire.com/sc3/scroads/sc700-709.html#sc700 The Highways of South Carolina: SC 700]\n\n[[Category:State highways in South Carolina|700]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Charleston County, South Carolina|South Carolina Highway 700]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Charleston, South Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox road\n|state=SC\n|type=SC\n|route=700\n|alternate_name=\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-lat=32.689|frame-long=-80.083|zoom=10|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/South Carolina Highway 700}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|length_mi=20.38\n|length_round=2\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"SCDOT GIS\"/>\n|established=\n|direction_a=West\n|terminus_a=[[Dead end (street)|Dead end]] in [[Rockville, South Carolina|Rockville]]\n|junction={{Jct|state=SC|SC|171}} in [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]]\n|direction_b=East\n|terminus_b={{Jct|state=SC|US|17}} in Charleston\n|counties=[[Charleston County, South Carolina|Charleston]]\n|previous_type=SC\n|previous_route=692\n|next_type=SC\n|next_route=702\n}}\n\n'''South Carolina Highway 700''' ('''SC 700''') is a [[state highway]] in the U.S. state of [[South Carolina]]. Known for most of its length as Maybank Highway, the state highway runs {{convert|20.38|mi|km}} from a [[Dead end (street)|dead end]] in [[Rockville, South Carolina|Rockville]] east to [[U.S. Route 17 in South Carolina|U.S. Highway 17]] (US 17) in [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]]. SC 700 connects Charleston with [[James Island (South Carolina)|James Island]], [[Johns Island, South Carolina|Johns Island]], and [[Wadmalaw Island]] in southwestern [[Charleston County, South Carolina|Charleston County]].\n\n==Route description==\nSC 700 begins at a dead end in the town of Rockville on Wadmalaw Island. The terminus is on the north side of Bohicket Creek, which separates Wadmalaw Island from [[Seabrook Island]], a short distance east of Bohicket Creek's mouth on the [[Edisto River|North Edisto River]]. The state highway heads northeast as Maybank Highway, a two-lane road that passes by the [[Charleston Tea Plantation]], the only working tea plantation in the United States, and near the [[Firefly Distillery]], which is on Bear Bluff Road on the portion of the island north of Leadenwah Creek. SR 700 crosses Church Creek onto Johns Island, enters an outlying section of the city of Charleston, and arrives at the main crossroads of the island near the site of the venerable [[Angel Oak]]. Main Road heads north from the junction through the northern part of the island before crossing the [[Stono River]] on the [[John F. Limehouse Memorial Bridge]] to meet US 17 between [[Rantowles, South Carolina|Rantowles]] and Charleston. Bohicket Road heads south toward Seabrook Island and Kiawah Island. SC 700 continues east and near the eastern end of the island intersects River Road, which leads south to [[Charleston Executive Airport]].<ref name=\"SCDOT County Maps\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps SC 700\"/>\n\nSC 700 expands to four lanes and crosses Pennys Creek and the Stono River on the high-level [[Paul Gelegotis Bridge]] and enters James Island. The highway passes through a golf course and along the south side of the historic [[Riverland Terrace]] neighborhood. SC 700 continues into a commercial area where the highway has a [[wye (rail)|wye]]-type junction with [[South Carolina Highway 171|SC 171]] (Folly Road) west of the [[McLeod Plantation]] and Charleston Country Club. Old Folly Road is used for the movements from eastbound SC 700 to southbound SC 171 and from northbound SC 171 to westbound SC 700. SC 700 and SC 171 head north concurrently on Folly Road, which has two lanes northbound and three lanes southbound. The highways enter the [[West Ashley]] section of Charleston by crossing Wappoo Creek, part of the [[Intracoastal Waterway]], on a [[Wappoo Creek Bridge|drawbridge]] named for [[Burnet R. Maybank]]. SC 700 and SC 171 diverge at a directional intersection that does not allow access from southbound SR 171 to eastbound SC 700. SC 171 heads north as Wesley Drive and is used to access southbound US 17 (Savannah Highway) and [[South Carolina Highway 61|SC 61]] (St. Andrews Boulevard). SC 700 heads northeast as five-lane Folly Road (three lanes westbound and two lanes eastbound) to its eastern terminus at a partial interchange with US 17 just west of the U.S. Highway's interchange with SC 61 and its bridges over the [[Ashley River (South Carolina)|Ashley River]]. The interchange allows access between SC 700 and US 17 in the direction of the peninsular section of Charleston.<ref name=\"SCDOT County Maps\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps SC 700\"/>\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{jcttop|length_ref=<ref name=\"SCDOT GIS\"/>|state=SC|county=Charleston}}\n{{SCint\n|location=Rockville\n|mile=0.00\n|road=[[Dead end (street)|Dead end]]\n|notes=Western terminus\n}}\n{{SCint\n|location=Charleston\n|lspan=3\n|mile=18.99\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=SC|SC|171|dir1=south|name1=Folly Road|city1=Folly Beach}}\n|notes=Western end of SC&nbsp;171 concurrency\n}}\n{{SCint\n|mile=19.96\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=SC|SC|171|dir1=north|name1=Wesley Drive|to2=y|US|17|dir2=south|SC|61|city1=North Charleston|location2=[[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]]}}\n|notes=Eastern end of SC&nbsp;171 concurrency\n}}\n{{SCint\n|mile=20.38\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=SC|US|17|dir1=north|name1=Savannah Highway|city1=Charleston|city2=Mount Pleasant}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus; southbound exit from and northbound entrance to US&nbsp;17\n}}\n{{Jctbtm|keys=concur,incomplete}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"SCDOT GIS\">{{cite map|publisher=[[South Carolina Department of Transportation]]|title=Highways - Zipped Shapefile of roads maintained by SCDOT - Statewide|url=http://dbw.scdot.org/GISMapping/pdfs/GIS/Statewide_Highways_2012.zip|format=ESRI shapefile|year=2012|accessdate=2012-05-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Google Maps SC 700\">{{google maps|url=https://maps.google.com/maps?saddr=S+Carolina+700+E&daddr=Folly+Rd&hl=en&sll=32.600952,-80.192868&sspn=0.00442,0.010568&geocode=FVxv8QEdGFU4-w%3BFTQv9AEd2Mg7-w&t=h&mra=ls&z=11|title=South Carolina Highway 700|accessdate=2012-05-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"SCDOT County Maps\">{{cite web|url=http://dbw.scdot.org/GISMapping/default.aspx|title=General County Highway Maps|publisher=South Carolina Department of Transportation|accessdate=2012-05-31}}\n*[http://dbw.scdot.org/GISMapping/pdfs/County/Charleston_County.pdf Charleston County] (PDF)\n</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML}}\n{{commonscat}}\n*[http://www.angelfire.com/sc3/scroads/sc700-709.html#sc700 The Highways of South Carolina: SC 700]\n\n[[Category:State highways in South Carolina|700]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Charleston County, South Carolina|South Carolina Highway 700]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Charleston, South Carolina]]\n", "name_user": "Mist6820", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Carolina_Highway_700"}
{"title_page": "Ablation casting", "text_new": "'''Ablation casting''' is a variation of [[sand casting]] involving a [[soluble]] [[binder (material)|binder]]. The [[Molding (process)|mold]] is dissolved and washed away, allowing rapid cooling of the casting.<ref>{{cite web|last=Grassi|first=J|title=The Ablation Casting Process|url=http://www.scientific.net/MSF.618-619.591.pdf|accessdate=6 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n== References == \n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Casting (manufacturing)]]\n\n\n{{manufacturing-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Ablation casting''' is a variation of [[sand casting]] involving a [[soluble]] [[binder (material)|binder]]. The [[mold]] is dissolved and washed away, allowing rapid cooling of the casting.<ref>{{cite web|last=Grassi|first=J|title=The Ablation Casting Process|url=http://www.scientific.net/MSF.618-619.591.pdf|accessdate=6 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n== References == \n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Casting (manufacturing)]]\n\n\n{{manufacturing-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMold(link changed toMolding (process)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ablation_casting"}
{"title_page": "1868 Arica earthquake", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox earthquake\n|title = 1868 Arica earthquake\n|map2 = {{Location map+ | Peru\n| AlternativeMap = Peru physical map.svg\n| places =\n{{Location map~|Peru|lat=-12.04|long=-77.03|label=[[Lima]]|position=left||label_size=120|mark=Blue pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Peru|lat=-18.48|long=-70.33|label=[[Arica]]|position=right||label_size=120|mark=Blue pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Peru|lat=-18.5|long=-71.0|position=left||marksize=45|mark=Bullseye1.png}}\n| relief = yes\n| label =\n| lat =\n| long =\n| mark =\n| marksize =\n| position =\n| width = 250\n| float = right\n| caption = \n}}\n| pre-1900  = yes\n|local-date = {{Start-date|df=yes|13 August 1868}}\n|local-time = 16:45\n|magnitude = 8.5\u20139.0 {{M|w|link=y}} (est.)\n|depth =\n|location = {{coord|-18.5|-71.0|type:event|display=inline,title}}<ref name=\"IISEE\">{{cite web|url=http://iisee.kenken.go.jp/utsu/index_eng.html|title=Catalog of Damaging Earthquakes in the World (Through 2007)|last=IISEE|accessdate=28 February 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100306180217/http://iisee.kenken.go.jp/utsu/index_eng.html| archivedate= 6 March 2010 | url-status=live}}</ref>\n|countries affected = [[Peru]] and northern [[Chile]]\n|tsunami =\n|intensity = [[Mercalli intensity scale|XI (''Extreme'')]]<ref name=\"NGDC\"/>\n|casualties = 25,000+\n}}\n\n[[File:Arica after the earthquake (1868).JPG|thumb|Arica after the earthquake and tsunami]]\n[[File:USS Wateree (1863).jpg|thumb|The [[USS Wateree (1863)|USS ''Wateree'']] beached at Arica, {{Convert|430|yd|m}} inland]]\n[[File:Arica Peru 1868.jpg|thumb|Sketches of Arica after the earthquake and tsunami from the ''[[Illustrated London News]]'']]\n\nThe '''1868 Arica earthquake''' occurred on 13 August 1868, near [[Arica]], then part of [[Peru]], now part of [[Chile]], at 21:30 [[UTC]]. It had an estimated magnitude between 8.5 and 9.0. A [[tsunami]] (or multiple tsunamis) in the [[Pacific Ocean]] was produced by the earthquake, which was recorded in [[Hawaii]], [[Japan]], [[Australia]], and [[New Zealand]].<ref name=\"USGS\">{{cite web|url=https://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/world/events/1868_08_13.php |title=Arica, Peru (now Chile) 1868 August 13 21:30 UTC |last=USGS |date=26 October 2009 |work=Historic Earthquakes |accessdate=28 February 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100116170411/http://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/world/events/1868_08_13.php |archivedate=16 January 2010 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref>[http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=TS18680829.2.13&srpos=160&e=13-08-1868-----10--151-byDA---0wave-ARTICLE- Latest from Australia], ''Star'', Issue 92, 29 August 1868, Page 3</ref>\n\n==Tectonic setting==\nThe earthquake occurred along the boundary between the [[Nazca Plate]] and the [[South American Plate]]. The earthquake was likely a result of [[thrust fault|thrust-faulting]], caused by the [[subduction]] of the Nazca plate beneath the South American plate.<ref name=\"Rabinovich\"/>\n\nThe coasts of Peru and Chile have a history of great [[megathrust earthquake]]s originating from this plate boundary, such as the [[1960 Valdivia earthquake]] and the [[2010 Chile earthquake]].\n\n==Damage==\nThe earthquake caused almost complete destruction in the southern part of Peru, including [[Arica Province (Peru)|Arica]], [[Tacna]], [[Moquegua]], [[Mollendo]], [[Ilo, Peru|Ilo]], [[Iquique]], [[Torata District|Torata]] and [[Arequipa]],<ref name=\"USGS\"/><ref name=\"Zamudio\"/> resulting in an estimated 25,000 casualties.<ref name=\"IISEE\"/>\n\nThe tsunami drove three ships anchored in port nearly {{convert|800|m|abbr=on}} inland: the 1560-ton Peruvian [[corvette]] ''America'', the [[USS Wateree (1863)|U.S. gunboat ''Wateree'']] and the U.S. store ship ''Fredonia'', which was completely destroyed.<ref name=\"USGS\"/><ref name=\"Zamudio\">{{cite web|url=http://horizon.documentation.ird.fr/exl-doc/pleins_textes/divers09-03/010040371.pdf|title=Seismic hazard assessment in the Peru-Chile border region|last=Zamudio|first=Y.|author2=Berrocal J. & Fernandes C.|year=2005|work=6th International Symposium on Andean Geodynamics|pages=813\u2013816|accessdate=28 February 2010}}</ref> The English [[brig]] ''Cha\u00f1arcillo'' and two Chilean [[schooner]]s, ''Rosa Rivera'' and ''Regalon'', were also lost.<ref name=\"Allen\">{{cite book|last=Allen|first=G.W.|title=The Great South American Earthquakes of 1868|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m6L1O1hxqzkC&pg=PA603|accessdate=6 December 2010|series=Harper's New Monthly Magazine|date=April 1869|page=613}}</ref> The port city of [[Pisco, Peru|Pisco]] was razed.<ref name=\"Okal\"/>\n\nThe tsunami caused considerable damage in Hawaii, washing out a bridge along the Waiohi River. In New Zealand, it is the only fatal tsunami on record, causing substantial damage on the [[Chatham Islands]] and an estimated 20 people washed out to sea.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12106143|title=NZ's only killer tsunami: What it means today|last=@Jamienzherald|first=Jamie Morton Science Reporter, NZ Herald jamie morton@nzherald co nz|date=13 August 2018|work=NZ Herald|access-date=2018-08-13|language=en-NZ|issn=1170-0777}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/science/106213804/only-deadly-nz-tsunami-on-record-hit-the-chathams-150-years-ago|title=Only deadly NZ tsunami on record hit the Chathams, 150 years ago|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref> On the mainland, [[Banks peninsula|Banks Peninsula]] was hardest hit with a Maori village and two houses washed away and boats damaged, and one death was recorded.<ref name=\"USGS\"/><ref>[http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=ODT18680828.2.18&srpos=147&e=13-08-1868-----10--141-byDA---0wave-ARTICLE- Arrival of the schooner Rifleman from the Chatham Islands], Otago Daily Times, Issue 2048, 28 August 1868, Page 3</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\n\n===Earthquake===\nTwo separate earthquakes have been described;<ref name=\"NGDC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ngdc.noaa.gov/nndc/struts/results?EQ_0=983&t=101650&s=8&d=22,26,13,12&nd=display|title=Page on 1868 event|last=NGDC|accessdate=28 February 2010}}</ref> they may both refer to the same event.<ref name=\"IISEE\"/>\n\nThe earthquake was felt over a wide  to {{convert|1400|km|abbr=on}} to the northwest in [[Samanco District|Samanco]], Peru and {{convert|224|km|abbr=on}} to the east in [[Bolivia]]. Estimates of its magnitude range from 8.5 to 9.0. A {{convert|600|km|abbr=on}} rupture length has been estimated from the [[Isoseismal map|pattern of isoseismals]] making it one of the largest fault breaks in modern times.<ref name=\"Okal\">{{cite journal|last=Okal|first=E.A.|author 2=Borrero J.C. & Synolakis C.E.|year=2006|title=Evaluation of Tsunami Risk from Regional Earthquakes at Pisco, Peru|journal=Bulletin of the Seismological Society of America|volume=96|issue=5|pages=1634\u20131648|url=http://www.earth.northwestern.edu/people/emile/PDF/EAO178.pdf|accessdate=1 March 2010|doi=10.1785/0120050158|bib code = 2006BuSSA..96.1634O |citeseerx=10.1.1.403.4006}}</ref>\n\nAbout 400 [[aftershock]]s were recorded by 25 August of that year.<ref name=\"USGS\"/>\n\nContemporary accounts say that the earthquake shaking lasted somewhere between five and ten minutes.<ref name=\"Allen\"/>\n\n===Tsunami===\nAlthough this event generated a tsunami that was noted across the Pacific, most of the associated damage was localised along the coasts of southern Peru and what is now northernmost Chile.<ref name=\"Rabinovich\"/> The first wave arrived at Arica 52 minutes after the earthquake, with a {{convert|12|m|abbr=on}} height, followed by the largest {{convert|16|m|abbr=on}} wave 73 minutes later.<ref name=\"Zamudio\"/>\n\n==Future risk==\nIn 2001 the Arica area was identified as forming part of a [[seismic gap]] between 15\u00b0 and 24\u00b0S, with no major earthquake since 1877. In accordance with this theory a major earthquake was considered likely to happen in the near future.<ref name=\"Rabinovich\">{{cite web|url=http://nthmp-history.pmel.noaa.gov/its2001/Separate_Papers/1-05_Rabinovich.pdf|title=Tsunami risk estimation for the coasts of Peru and northern Chile|last=Rabinovich|first=A.B.|author2=Kulikov E.A. & Thomson R.E.|year=2001|work=ITS 2001 Proceedings, Session 1|pages=281\u2013291|accessdate=28 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100721012643/http://nthmp-history.pmel.noaa.gov/its2001/Separate_Papers/1-05_Rabinovich.pdf|archive-date=21 July 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> More specifically, in 2005 a magnitude 8.6 event was forecast for the northern Chile part of the gap, the location of the subsequent [[2014 Iquique earthquake]]. An earthquake affecting the same sector of the plate boundary as the 1868 event with a magnitude of 8.8 was also forecast as likely to occur by 2126.<ref name=\"Zamudio\"/> A repeat of the 1868 event would probably cause more casualties, because of the increase of population in areas at risk.\n\n==See also==\n* {{Portal-inline|Chile}}\n* {{Portal-inline|Peru}}\n* [[1877 Iquique earthquake]]\n* [[2014 Iquique earthquake]]\n* [[List of earthquakes in Chile]]\n* [[List of earthquakes in Peru]]\n* [[List of historical earthquakes]]\n* [[List of historical tsunamis]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|title=Arica 1868: Un Tsunami y Un Terremoto|url=http://www.memoriachilena.cl/temas/documento_detalle.asp?id=MC0064460|first=Manuel Fern\u00e1ndez|last=Canque|date=January 2007|publisher=[[University of Tarapac\u00e1]]|isbn=978-9562441940}}\n* {{citation|title=Un d\u00eda en la historia de Arica: 13 de agosto 1868|url=https://www.academia.edu/4228789|first=Manuel Fern\u00e1ndez|last=Canque|pages=33\u201347}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|position=left|1868 Arica earthquake}}\n\n{{Earthquakes in 1868}}\n{{Earthquakes in Chile}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1868 Arica Earthquake}}\n[[Category:1868 earthquakes|Arica]]\n[[Category:Megathrust earthquakes in Peru]]\n[[Category:Megathrust earthquakes in Chile]]\n[[Category:Arica|E]]\n[[Category:History of Arica y Parinacota Region|Arica earthquake]]\n[[Category:History of Tarapac\u00e1 Region|Arica earthquake]]\n[[Category:1868 tsunamis]]\n[[Category:1868 in Peru|Arica]]\n[[Category:1868 in Chile|Arica]]\n[[Category:Iquique Province|Arica Earthquake]]\n[[Category:Tsunamis in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:August 1868 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox earthquake\n|title = 1868 Arica earthquake\n|map2 = {{Location map+ | Peru\n| AlternativeMap = Peru physical map.svg\n| places =\n{{Location map~|Peru|lat=-12.04|long=-77.03|label=[[Lima]]|position=left||label_size=120|mark=Blue pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Peru|lat=-18.48|long=-70.33|label=[[Arica]]|position=right||label_size=120|mark=Blue pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Peru|lat=-18.5|long=-71.0|position=left||marksize=45|mark=Bullseye1.png}}\n| relief = yes\n| label =\n| lat =\n| long =\n| mark =\n| marksize =\n| position =\n| width = 250\n| float = right\n| caption = \n}}\n| pre-1900  = yes\n|local-date = {{Start-date|df=yes|13 August 1868}}\n|local-time = 16:45\n|magnitude = 8.5\u20139.0 {{M|w|link=y}} (est.)\n|depth =\n|location = {{coord|-18.5|-71.0|type:event|display=inline,title}}<ref name=\"IISEE\">{{cite web|url=http://iisee.kenken.go.jp/utsu/index_eng.html|title=Catalog of Damaging Earthquakes in the World (Through 2007)|last=IISEE|accessdate=28 February 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100306180217/http://iisee.kenken.go.jp/utsu/index_eng.html| archivedate= 6 March 2010 | url-status=live}}</ref>\n|countries affected = [[Peru]] and northern [[Chile]]\n|tsunami =\n|intensity = [[Mercalli intensity scale|XI (''Extreme'')]]<ref name=\"NGDC\"/>\n|casualties = 25,000+\n}}\n\n[[File:Arica after the earthquake (1868).JPG|thumb|Arica after the earthquake and tsunami]]\n[[File:USS Wateree (1863).jpg|thumb|The [[USS Wateree (1863)|USS ''Wateree'']] beached at Arica, {{Convert|430|yd|m}} inland]]\n[[File:Arica Peru 1868.jpg|thumb|Sketches of Arica after the earthquake and tsunami from the ''[[Illustrated London News]]'']]\n\nThe '''1868 Arica earthquake''' occurred on 13 August 1868, near [[Arica]], then part of [[Peru]], now part of [[Chile]], at 21:30 [[UTC]]. It had an estimated magnitude between 8.5 and 9.0. A [[tsunami]] (or multiple tsunamis) in the [[Pacific Ocean]] was produced by the earthquake, which was recorded in [[Hawaii]], [[Japan]], [[Australia]], and [[New Zealand]].<ref name=\"USGS\">{{cite web|url=https://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/world/events/1868_08_13.php |title=Arica, Peru (now Chile) 1868 August 13 21:30 UTC |last=USGS |date=26 October 2009 |work=Historic Earthquakes |accessdate=28 February 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100116170411/http://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/world/events/1868_08_13.php |archivedate=16 January 2010 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref>[http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=TS18680829.2.13&srpos=160&e=13-08-1868-----10--151-byDA---0wave-ARTICLE- Latest from Australia], ''Star'', Issue 92, 29 August 1868, Page 3</ref>\n\n==Tectonic setting==\nThe earthquake occurred along the boundary between the [[Nazca Plate]] and the [[South American Plate]]. The earthquake was likely a result of [[thrust fault|thrust-faulting]], caused by the [[subduction]] of the Nazca plate beneath the South American plate.<ref name=\"Rabinovich\"/>\n\nThe coasts of Peru and Chile have a history of great [[megathrust earthquake]]s originating from this plate boundary, such as the [[1960 Valdivia earthquake]] and the [[2010 Chile earthquake]].\n\n==Damage==\nThe earthquake caused almost complete destruction in the southern part of Peru, including [[Arica Province (Peru)|Arica]], [[Tacna]], [[Moquegua]], [[Mollendo]], [[Ilo, Peru|Ilo]], [[Iquique]], [[Torata District|Torata]] and [[Arequipa]],<ref name=\"USGS\"/><ref name=\"Zamudio\"/> resulting in an estimated 25,000 casualties.<ref name=\"IISEE\"/>\n\nThe tsunami drove three ships anchored in port nearly {{convert|800|m|abbr=on}} inland: the 1560-ton Peruvian [[corvette]] ''America'', the [[USS Wateree (1863)|U.S. gunboat ''Wateree'']] and the U.S. store ship ''Fredonia'', which was completely destroyed.<ref name=\"USGS\"/><ref name=\"Zamudio\">{{cite web|url=http://horizon.documentation.ird.fr/exl-doc/pleins_textes/divers09-03/010040371.pdf|title=Seismic hazard assessment in the Peru-Chile border region|last=Zamudio|first=Y.|author2=Berrocal J. & Fernandes C.|year=2005|work=6th International Symposium on Andean Geodynamics|pages=813\u2013816|accessdate=28 February 2010}}</ref> The English [[brig]] ''Cha\u00f1arcillo'' and two Chilean [[schooner]]s, ''Rosa Rivera'' and ''Regalon'', were also lost.<ref name=\"Allen\">{{cite book|last=Allen|first=G.W.|title=The Great South American Earthquakes of 1868|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m6L1O1hxqzkC&pg=PA603|accessdate=6 December 2010|series=Harper's New Monthly Magazine|date=April 1869|page=613}}</ref> The port city of [[Pisco, Peru|Pisco]] was razed.<ref name=\"Okal\"/>\n\nThe tsunami caused considerable damage in Hawaii, washing out a bridge along the Waiohi River. In New Zealand, it is the only fatal tsunami on record, causing substantial damage on the [[Chatham Islands]] and an estimated 20 people washed out to sea.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12106143|title=NZ's only killer tsunami: What it means today|last=@Jamienzherald|first=Jamie Morton Science Reporter, NZ Herald jamie morton@nzherald co nz|date=13 August 2018|work=NZ Herald|access-date=2018-08-13|language=en-NZ|issn=1170-0777}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/science/106213804/only-deadly-nz-tsunami-on-record-hit-the-chathams-150-years-ago|title=Only deadly NZ tsunami on record hit the Chathams, 150 years ago|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref> On the mainland, [[Banks peninsula|Banks Peninsula]] was hardest hit with a Maori village and two houses washed away and boats damaged, and one death was recorded.<ref name=\"USGS\"/><ref>[http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=ODT18680828.2.18&srpos=147&e=13-08-1868-----10--141-byDA---0wave-ARTICLE- Arrival of the schooner Rifleman from the Chatham Islands], Otago Daily Times, Issue 2048, 28 August 1868, Page 3</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\n\n===Earthquake===\nTwo separate earthquakes have been described;<ref name=\"NGDC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ngdc.noaa.gov/nndc/struts/results?EQ_0=983&t=101650&s=8&d=22,26,13,12&nd=display|title=Page on 1868 event|last=NGDC|accessdate=28 February 2010}}</ref> they may both refer to the same event.<ref name=\"IISEE\"/>\n\nThe earthquake was felt over a wide area, up to {{convert|1400|km|abbr=on}} to the northwest in [[Samanco District|Samanco]], Peru and {{convert|224|km|abbr=on}} to the east in [[Bolivia]]. Estimates of its magnitude range from 8.5 to 9.0. A {{convert|600|km|abbr=on}} rupture length has been estimated from the [[Isoseismal map|pattern of isoseismals]] making it one of the largest fault breaks in modern times.<ref name=\"Okal\">{{cite journal|last=Okal|first=E.A.|author2=Borrero J.C. & Synolakis C.E.|year=2006|title=Evaluation of Tsunami Risk from Regional Earthquakes at Pisco, Peru|journal=Bulletin of the Seismological Society of America|volume=96|issue=5|pages=1634\u20131648|url=http://www.earth.northwestern.edu/people/emile/PDF/EAO178.pdf|accessdate=1 March 2010|doi=10.1785/0120050158|bibcode = 2006BuSSA..96.1634O |citeseerx=10.1.1.403.4006}}</ref>\n\nAbout 400 [[aftershock]]s were recorded by 25 August of that year.<ref name=\"USGS\"/>\n\nContemporary accounts say that the earthquake shaking lasted somewhere between five and ten minutes.<ref name=\"Allen\"/>\n\n===Tsunami===\nAlthough this event generated a tsunami that was noted across the Pacific, most of the associated damage was localised along the coasts of southern Peru and what is now northernmost Chile.<ref name=\"Rabinovich\"/> The first wave arrived at Arica 52 minutes after the earthquake, with a {{convert|12|m|abbr=on}} height, followed by the largest {{convert|16|m|abbr=on}} wave 73 minutes later.<ref name=\"Zamudio\"/>\n\n==Future risk==\nIn 2001 the Arica area was identified as forming part of a [[seismic gap]] between 15\u00b0 and 24\u00b0S, with no major earthquake since 1877. In accordance with this theory a major earthquake was considered likely to happen in the near future.<ref name=\"Rabinovich\">{{cite web|url=http://nthmp-history.pmel.noaa.gov/its2001/Separate_Papers/1-05_Rabinovich.pdf|title=Tsunami risk estimation for the coasts of Peru and northern Chile|last=Rabinovich|first=A.B.|author2=Kulikov E.A. & Thomson R.E.|year=2001|work=ITS 2001 Proceedings, Session 1|pages=281\u2013291|accessdate=28 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100721012643/http://nthmp-history.pmel.noaa.gov/its2001/Separate_Papers/1-05_Rabinovich.pdf|archive-date=21 July 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> More specifically, in 2005 a magnitude 8.6 event was forecast for the northern Chile part of the gap, the location of the subsequent [[2014 Iquique earthquake]]. An earthquake affecting the same sector of the plate boundary as the 1868 event with a magnitude of 8.8 was also forecast as likely to occur by 2126.<ref name=\"Zamudio\"/> A repeat of the 1868 event would probably cause more casualties, because of the increase of population in areas at risk.\n\n==See also==\n* {{Portal-inline|Chile}}\n* {{Portal-inline|Peru}}\n* [[1877 Iquique earthquake]]\n* [[2014 Iquique earthquake]]\n* [[List of earthquakes in Chile]]\n* [[List of earthquakes in Peru]]\n* [[List of historical earthquakes]]\n* [[List of historical tsunamis]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|title=Arica 1868: Un Tsunami y Un Terremoto|url=http://www.memoriachilena.cl/temas/documento_detalle.asp?id=MC0064460|first=Manuel Fern\u00e1ndez|last=Canque|date=January 2007|publisher=[[University of Tarapac\u00e1]]|isbn=978-9562441940}}\n* {{citation|title=Un d\u00eda en la historia de Arica: 13 de agosto 1868|url=https://www.academia.edu/4228789|first=Manuel Fern\u00e1ndez|last=Canque|pages=33\u201347}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|position=left|1868 Arica earthquake}}\n\n{{Earthquakes in 1868}}\n{{Earthquakes in Chile}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1868 Arica Earthquake}}\n[[Category:1868 earthquakes|Arica]]\n[[Category:Megathrust earthquakes in Peru]]\n[[Category:Megathrust earthquakes in Chile]]\n[[Category:Arica|E]]\n[[Category:History of Arica y Parinacota Region|Arica earthquake]]\n[[Category:History of Tarapac\u00e1 Region|Arica earthquake]]\n[[Category:1868 tsunamis]]\n[[Category:1868 in Peru|Arica]]\n[[Category:1868 in Chile|Arica]]\n[[Category:Iquique Province|Arica Earthquake]]\n[[Category:Tsunamis in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:August 1868 events]]\n", "name_user": "2605:e000:160f:21ac:94b2:2082:86d6:711", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCharacteristics)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1868_Arica_earthquake"}
{"title_page": "Spiraea alba", "text_new": "{{For|other plants called meadowsweet|meadowsweet (disambiguation)}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = Spiraea.alba.-.lindsey.jpg\n| genus = Spiraea\n| species = alba\n| authority = [[Johann Philipp Du Roi|Du Roi]]\n| synonyms =\n    {{Plainlist | style = margin-left: 1em; text-indent: -1em; |\n*''Eleiosina obovata'' <small>Raf. ex Ser.</small>\n*''Spiraea ciliata'' <small>Raf.</small>\n*''Spiraea cuneifolia'' <small>Borkh.</small>\n*''Spiraea flexuosa'' <small>Raf.</small>\n*''Spiraea lanceolata'' <small>Borkh.</small>\n*''Spiraea lancifolia'' <small>Hoffmanns. ex K.Koch</small>\n*''Spiraea latifolia'' <small>(Sol.) Borkh.</small>\n*''Spiraea paniculata'' <small>(Willd.) G.Don</small>\n*''Spiraea undulata'' <small>Borkh.</small>\n    }}\n| synonyms_ref = <ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.theplantlist.org/tpl1.1/record/rjp-1282\n|title=The Plant List: A Working List of All Plant Species\n|accessdate=June 10, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Spiraea alba''''', commonly known as '''meadowsweet''',<ref name=GRIN>{{GRIN | accessdate=10 June 2014}}</ref> '''white meadowsweet''',<ref>{{PLANTS|id=SPAL2|taxon=Spiraea alba|accessdate=27 November 2015}}</ref> '''narrowleaf meadowsweet''',{{citation needed|date=June 2014}} '''pale bridewort''',<ref name=BSBI07>{{cite web |title=BSBI List 2007 |publisher=Botanical Society of Britain and Ireland |url=http://www.bsbi.org.uk/BSBIList2007.xls |format=xls |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6VqJ46atN?url=http://www.bsbi.org.uk/BSBIList2007.xls |archive-date=2015-01-25 |access-date=2014-10-17 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> or '''pipestem''',{{citation needed|date=June 2014}} is native to the wet soils of the [[Allegheny Mountains]] and other portions of eastern [[North America]],<ref>{{cite book |author=Venable, N.J.; Service, W.V.U.C.E. |year=1996  |title=Common Summer Wildflowers of West Virginia |publisher=West Virginia University Extension Service}}</ref> but is currently endangered in the state of Missouri. It is [[naturalized]] in other parts of the world.<ref name=GRIN/>\n\nNarrowleaf meadowsweet shrubs often reach 8 feet in height with a spread of 3\u20134 feet. This species is often the most conspicuous part of the vegetation in its habitat, taking up large areas of ground. Its leaves are glossy yellow-green, oblong or lance-shaped, and toothed on the edges, and its twigs are tough and yellowish brown. Fall foliage is golden yellow. The white and sometimes pink fragrant flowers grow in spike-like clusters at the ends of the branches, blooming from early summer through September. The brown fruit, which persists after flowering, is a distinctive feature of all ''Spiraea'' species.<ref>http://newfs.s3.amazonaws.com/taxon-images-1000s1000/Rosaceae/spiraea-alba-latifolia-fr-ahaines.jpg\n</ref>\n\nButterflies and other beneficial insects visit the plant for nectar and pollen. In autumn brown seed capsules appear and are fed on by songbirds. Glossy green foliage turns yellow in the fall. Deer tend to leave this plant alone. Meadowsweet is a host plant for the larvae of the [[Celastrina argiolus|spring azure butterfly]]. The blooms make a good cut flower.\n\nThe hollow, upright stems were used historically as pipe stems.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{Commons-inline}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q7577709}}\n\n[[Category:Spiraea|alba]]\n[[Category:Flora of North America]]\n\n\n{{amygdaloideae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{For|other plants called meadowsweet|meadowsweet (disambiguation)}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = Spiraea.alba.-.lindsey.jpg\n| genus = Spiraea\n| species = alba\n| authority = [[Johann Philipp Du Roi|Du Roi]]\n| synonyms =\n    {{Plainlist | style = margin-left: 1em; text-indent: -1em; |\n*''Eleiosina obovata'' <small>Raf. ex Ser.</small>\n*''Spiraea ciliata'' <small>Raf.</small>\n*''Spiraea cuneifolia'' <small>Borkh.</small>\n*''Spiraea flexuosa'' <small>Raf.</small>\n*''Spiraea lanceolata'' <small>Borkh.</small>\n*''Spiraea lancifolia'' <small>Hoffmanns. ex K.Koch</small>\n*''Spiraea latifolia'' <small>(Sol.) Borkh.</small>\n*''Spiraea paniculata'' <small>(Willd.) G.Don</small>\n*''Spiraea undulata'' <small>Borkh.</small>\n    }}\n| synonyms_ref = <ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.theplantlist.org/tpl1.1/record/rjp-1282\n|title=The Plant List: A Working List of All Plant Species\n|accessdate=June 10, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Spiraea alba''''', commonly known as '''meadowsweet''',<ref name=GRIN>{{GRIN | accessdate=10 June 2014}}</ref> '''white meadowsweet''',<ref>{{PLANTS|id=SPAL2|taxon=Spiraea alba|accessdate=27 November 2015}}</ref> '''narrowleaf meadowsweet''',{{citation needed|date=June 2014}} '''pale bridewort''',<ref name=BSBI07>{{cite web |title=BSBI List 2007 |publisher=Botanical Society of Britain and Ireland |url=http://www.bsbi.org.uk/BSBIList2007.xls |format=xls |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6VqJ46atN?url=http://www.bsbi.org.uk/BSBIList2007.xls |archive-date=2015-01-25 |access-date=2014-10-17 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> or '''pipestem''',{{citation needed|date=June 2014}} is native to the wet soils of the [[Allegheny Mountains]] and other portions of eastern [[North America]],<ref>{{cite book |author=Venable, N.J.; Service, W.V.U.C.E. |year=1996  |title=Common Summer Wildflowers of West Virginia |publisher=West Virginia University Extension Service}}</ref> but is currently endangered in the state of Missouri. It is [[naturalized]] in other parts of the world.<ref name=GRIN/>\n\nNarrowleaf meadowsweet shrubs often reach 8 feet in height with a spread of 3\u20134 feet. This species is often the most conspicuous part of the vegetation in its habitat, taking up large areas of ground. Its leaves are glossy yellow-green, oblong or lance-shaped, and toothed on the edges, and its twigs are tough and yellowish brown.  Fall foliage is golden yellow.  The white and sometimes pink fragrant flowers grow in spike-like clusters at the ends of the branches, blooming from early summer through September. The brown fruit, which persists after flowering, is a distinctive feature of all ''Spiraea'' species.<ref>http://newfs.s3.amazonaws.com/taxon-images-1000s1000/Rosaceae/spiraea-alba-latifolia-fr-ahaines.jpg\n</ref>\n\nButterflies and other beneficial insects visit the plant for nectar and pollen. In autumn brown seed capsules appear and are fed on by songbirds. Glossy green foliage turns yellow in the fall. Deer tend to leave this plant alone. Meadowsweet is a host plant for the larvae of the [[Celastrina argiolus|spring azure butterfly]].  The blooms make a good cut flower.\n\nThe hollow, upright stems were used historically as pipe stems.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{Commons-inline}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q7577709}}\n\n[[Category:Spiraea|alba]]\n[[Category:Flora of North America]]\n\n\n{{amygdaloideae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Harrumphings", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed double spaces", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spiraea_alba"}
{"title_page": "Caleb McLaughlin", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Caleb McLaughlin\n| image              = Caleb McLaughlin by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption            = McLaughlin at the 2017 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birth_name         = Caleb Reginald McLaughlin\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|2001|10|13}}\n| birth_place        = [[Carmel, New York|Carmel]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| occupation         = Actor\n| years_active       = 2012\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Caleb Reginald McLaughlin'''<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Sean Hayes/Stranger Things Kids/Sheryl Crow|episode-link=|series=The Ellen DeGeneres Show|series-link=The Ellen DeGeneres Show|network=|date=25 October 2017|season=15|number=37}}</ref> (born October 13, 2001)<ref>{{cite web|title=The kids of \"Stranger Things\" wishing Caleb McLaughlin (Lucas) a happy birthday is pure #friendshipgoals|url=https://hellogiggles.com/reviews-coverage/tv-shows/kids-of-stranger-things-all-wished-caleb-mclaughlin-a-happy-birthday/|website=[[HelloGiggles]]|first=Sarah|last=Terry|date=October 13, 2016}}</ref> is an American actor and singer. He is known for playing Lucas Sinclair in the Netflix series ''[[Stranger Things]]''. McLaughlin began his career when he appeared in an opera called ''Lost in the Stars'' in [[Cooperstown, New York]] at the Glimmerglass Opera House.  He then played on the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] stage as Young Simba in the musical ''[[The Lion King (musical)|The Lion King]]''. In 2017, McLaughlin appeared in the [[BET]] miniseries ''[[The New Edition Story]]'' as young Ricky Bell.\n\n==Early life==\nMcLaughlin grew up in [[Carmel, New York]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Caleb McLaughlin Biography, Celebrity Facts and Awards|url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/caleb-mclaughlin/bio/841502/|accessdate=August 24, 2015|website=[[TV Guide]]|date=August 20, 2015}}</ref> He attended Kent Primary School and later attended [[George Fischer Middle School]] for one year. He studied dance for a year at Happy Feet Dance School in Carmel, New York and then at [[The Harlem School of the Arts]] under Chloe E. Matteson, former ''[[The Lion King (musical)|Lion King]]'' producer.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Silva|first1=Tiffany|title=CALEB MCLAUGHLIN IS HAVING A GREAT START TO 2017|url=https://bckonline.com/2017/01/10/caleb-mclaughlin-is-having-a-great-start-to-2017/|website=bckonline.com|accessdate=January 21, 2018|date=January 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Cabiles|first1=Janroe|title=Caleb McLaughlin: Stranger Stages|url=http://statusmagonline.com/features/caleb-mclaughlin-interview-july-2017/|website=statusmagonline.com|accessdate=January 21, 2018|date=July 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''Noah Dreams of Origami Fortunes''\n| Noah\n| Short film<ref>{{cite web|last=Dunmore|first=Royce|title=Noah Dreams of Origami Fortunes (2012)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2265704/|website=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=September 19, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n||2019\n| ''[[High Flying Bird]]''\n| Darius\n|\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Concrete Cowboys (2020 film)|Concrete Cowboys]]''\n| Cole\n| Post-production\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2013\n| ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''\n| Kid\n| Episode: \"Born Psychopath\"\n|-\n| ''[[Unforgettable (2011 TV series)|Unforgettable]]''\n| Older Brother\n| Episode: \"New Hundred\"\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Forever (2014 TV series)|Forever]]''\n| Alejandro\n| Episode: \"The Pugilist Break\"\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[What Would You Do? (ABC News series)|What Would You Do?]]''\n| Caleb/Secret Actor\n| Episode 2\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Shades of Blue (TV series)|Shades of Blue]]''\n| Jay-Jay\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| 2016\u2013present\n| ''[[Stranger Things]]''\n| Lucas Sinclair\n| Main Character\n|-\n| 2016 \n| ''[[Blue Bloods (TV series)|Blue Bloods]]''\n| Tony Lane\n| Episode: \"For the Community\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2017\n| ''[[The New Edition Story]]''\n| Ricky Bell (age 10-15)\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Lip Sync Battle]]''\n| Caleb\n| Episode: \"The Cast of ''Stranger Things\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2018 \n| ''[[Final Space]]''\n| Young Gary (voice) \n| Episode: \"Chapter 4\"\n|- \n| ''[[Summer Camp Island]]''\n| Ghost (voice) \n| Episode: \"Ghost the Boy\"\n|}\n\n=== Web series ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Brawl Stars|Brawl with the Stars]]''\n| Himself\n| Episode: \"Brawl with the Stars (feat. [[Finn Wolfhard]] and Caleb McLaughlin)\"\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Artist\n! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2017\n| ''Jimmy Fallon's [[74th Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globes 2017]] Opening''\n| [[Jimmy Fallon]]\n|\n|-\n| ''Santa's Coming For Us''\n| [[Sia (musician)|Sia]]\n|\n|}\n\n===Stage===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Location\n|-\n| 2012\u201314\n| ''[[The Lion King (musical)|The Lion King]]''\n| Young [[Simba]]\n| [[Minskoff Theatre]], Broadway<ref>{{cite web|last=Velez|first=Ali|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/alivelez/you-guys-the-little-kids-from-stranger-things-can-really-sin|title=We Need To Talk About The Musical Talents Of The Kids From \"Stranger Things\"|website=[[BuzzFeed]]|date=August 2, 2016|accessdate=September 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/person/caleb-mclaughlin-vault-0000123644|title=Caleb McLaughlin|website=[[Playbill]]|accessdate=September 19, 2016}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n! {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n| [[38th Young Artist Awards|2017]]\n| [[38th Young Artist Awards|Young Artist Awards]]\n| [[38th Young Artist Awards#Best Performance in a Digital TV Series or Film|Best Performance in a Digital TV Series or Film&nbsp;\u